and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chandos","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Candos in Illeville-sur-Montfort (Eure)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":4,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Chandos III was born in 1102, in Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales, his father, Roger de Chandos III, was 27 and his mother, Margaret Giffard, was 28. He married Emma of Snodhill about 1127, in Snodhill, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1193, in Snodhill, Herefordshire, England, at the age of 91, and was buried in Peterchurch, Herefordshire, England."},"et":{"1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1107–Female":"1107–Surnud","1126–1156":"1126–1156","1128–1196":"1128–1196","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1075–1142":"1075–1142","after 1193":"pärast 1193","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","1196":"1196","1193":"1193","1107":"1107","1139":"1139","1106":"1106","1128":"1128","1105":"1105","1126":"1126","1213":"1213","1102":"1102","about 1127":"umbes 1127","1156":"1156","about 1128":"umbes 1128","about 1156":"umbes 1156","Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales","Newport, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Newport, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Snodhill, Herefordshire, England":"Snodhill, Herefordshire, England","Peterchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Peterchurch, Herefordshire, England","Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1107–Female":"1107–Kuollut","1126–1156":"1126–1156","1128–1196":"1128–1196","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1075–1142":"1075–1142","after 1193":"1193 jälkeen","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","1196":"1196","1193":"1193","1107":"1107","1139":"1139","1106":"1106","1128":"1128","1105":"1105","1126":"1126","1213":"1213","1102":"1102","about 1127":"noin 1127","1156":"1156","about 1128":"noin 1128","about 1156":"noin 1156","Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales","Newport, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Newport, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Snodhill, Herefordshire, England":"Snodhill, Herefordshire, England","Peterchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Peterchurch, Herefordshire, England","Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1107–Female":"1107–Décédée","1126–1156":"1126–1156","1128–1196":"1128–1196","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1075–1142":"1075–11